strategy_free: Before the interview started, I figured that it would be better to plan for a worst-case scenario rather than a best-case scenario. A worst case scenario would involve the interviewer having substantial reason to believe in my culpability and this was indeed the case. In that regard, I knew I needed to have an alibi for the numerous supicious behaviours I did (e.g., stealing a key from a coat, putting a pill in the milk). I believe that some of the most effective deceptions are those that are blended with the truth. To that regard, I came up with what I believed (and hoped) were believable explanations for the otherwise suspicious behaviours I did (e.g., I said that I felt Tim's coat because I wanted to know the material, that I did lift something from the pockets because I noticed candy in there, that I grabbed Tim's mail because I was there anyway and I figured I'd give it to him when I saw him, that I was able to enter his office because it was left ajar). I'd like to think that all of my explanations have a strong degree of plausibility to them. Obviously if they have footage of me committing each crime as it happened, then I'd be doomed either way, but if they only have ambiguous footage of me (e.g., of me approaching Tim's coat, of me entering Tim's office) then these alibis may be sufficient to induce reasonable doubt on the part of the investigator(s) and any subsequent juries.
change_strategy_free: Nope; I stuck to the plan (assume they have substantial evidence/knowledge of my activities, come up with alibis that explain what those behaviours were for).

I wasn't going to deny that I was in the building at all, as it was pretty clear that a company like that would have security cameras all over the place and that I would be seen the moment I entered. 

So my strategy was to admit I had done the things, but act like I was there on behalf of the company to fix their wifi issues with video conferencing by installing a router - basically emphasising things like the fact that the phone had the password on the home screen or that I knew the conference room pin code (so didn't break in) and deemphasising things like the fact I took a schedule (so saying I thought it could be a map) or had gloves on (poor circulation). If asked, I hoped that my confidence walking into the building would have convinced them that I was there on legitimate business to fix IT issues. 

My primary goal was to shift blame away from Lepus and toward Testudo by acting as if I was just an innocent bystander caught in the middle of the action by other people. So perhaps I would have gotten jail time, but not as much and without implicating the organization in any way.
change_strategy_free:
I realized that admitting to everything would have caused trouble, so I selectively forgot things that would be important to a thief (like what the rooms looked like or room numbers/stairwell names) and emphasized things an IT person would often be concerned with (brand of the monitor, type of wifi network, windows issues, types of cables in the conference room). 

Also when I started, I tried to come across as a bit nervous and anxious (police station after all), but friendly wanting to try and help (such as asking the interviewer to repeat her name and apologizing for when I couldn't remember "key details" or about the phone).
